00:00:54.950 --> 00:00:57.530 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You know when I
was looking at all your work

00:00:57.530 --> 00:01:03.700 align:middle line:84%
over the years, I kept saying
to myself, this is scary stuff.

00:01:03.700 --> 00:01:06.070 align:middle line:90%
This isn't just pure science.

00:01:06.070 --> 00:01:08.320 align:middle line:90%
This isn't just manipulation.

00:01:08.320 --> 00:01:10.270 align:middle line:90%
This is control.

00:01:10.270 --> 00:01:14.325 align:middle line:84%
How did you get interested
in mind programming?

00:01:14.325 --> 00:01:18.730 align:middle line:10%
>>TAYLOR: That's a long story,
but it begins in years past

00:01:18.730 --> 00:01:22.950 align:middle line:10%
when I was practicing
criminalistics.

00:01:22.950 --> 00:01:28.810 align:middle line:10%
I found myself dealing with
lie detection scenarios,

00:01:28.810 --> 00:01:31.960 align:middle line:10%
as I was a lie detection
examiner for years.

00:01:31.960 --> 00:01:34.610 align:middle line:84%
And I heard that LA
Police Department

00:01:34.610 --> 00:01:39.000 align:middle line:84%
had utilized a technology,
a subliminal technology,

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:42.440 align:middle line:84%
to dehydrate the
cadets in the academy.

00:01:42.440 --> 00:01:44.340 align:middle line:84%
And the reason
they did so is they

00:01:44.340 --> 00:01:47.210 align:middle line:84%
were preparing for the
Los Angeles Olympics.

00:01:47.210 --> 00:01:50.990 align:middle line:84%
And of course, they had a
terrorist abduction scenario

00:01:50.990 --> 00:01:55.290 align:middle line:84%
that played out, like
there are so many hours

00:01:55.290 --> 00:01:57.730 align:middle line:84%
spent on the phone
in negotiation.

00:01:57.730 --> 00:02:00.120 align:middle line:84%
They would play
this white sound,

00:02:00.120 --> 00:02:03.680 align:middle line:84%
the sound of an air conditioner
or a heater in the background.

00:02:03.680 --> 00:02:07.040 align:middle line:84%
It would have hidden messages,
and those hidden messages

00:02:07.040 --> 00:02:12.210 align:middle line:84%
were designed to affect the
nervous system, dehydrate.

00:02:12.210 --> 00:02:16.370 align:middle line:84%
They would suggest
to the abductors

00:02:16.370 --> 00:02:19.960 align:middle line:84%
that they were in an area
that was contaminated,

00:02:19.960 --> 00:02:22.890 align:middle line:84%
and if they were
to see symptoms of,

00:02:22.890 --> 00:02:24.370 align:middle line:90%
they'd describe the symptoms.

00:02:24.370 --> 00:02:28.570 align:middle line:84%
And of course, the idea was that
by pumping this information in,

00:02:28.570 --> 00:02:30.850 align:middle line:84%
they would begin to
manifest the symptoms.

00:02:30.850 --> 00:02:35.490 align:middle line:84%
When I heard about this, I
was really amazed at the idea

00:02:35.490 --> 00:02:38.740 align:middle line:84%
that you can hide a
message that would affect

00:02:38.740 --> 00:02:40.694 align:middle line:90%
the human body in that way.

00:02:40.694 --> 00:02:42.110 align:middle line:84%
Well, the long and
the short of it

00:02:42.110 --> 00:02:46.130 align:middle line:84%
is I've never been able
to, despite attempts,

00:02:46.130 --> 00:02:48.750 align:middle line:84%
either confirm or get
that story denied.

00:02:48.750 --> 00:02:52.190 align:middle line:84%
But it changed the direction
of my career at that point.

00:02:52.190 --> 00:02:55.260 align:middle line:84%
Because I thought,
OK, now wait a minute.

00:02:55.260 --> 00:02:59.000 align:middle line:84%
If that can happen, I
can solve a major problem

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:00.180 align:middle line:90%
in lie detection.

00:03:00.180 --> 00:03:03.170 align:middle line:84%
20% percent, approximately,
of those people

00:03:03.170 --> 00:03:07.080 align:middle line:84%
that come in for a lie detection
test, they're inconclusive.

00:03:07.080 --> 00:03:09.372 align:middle line:90%
You have an honest person, but--

00:03:09.372 --> 00:03:10.830 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: He's
nervous or something.

00:03:10.830 --> 00:03:14.230 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Yes, so much
situational stress with them

00:03:14.230 --> 00:03:17.560 align:middle line:84%
that you can't say they
practiced deception,

00:03:17.560 --> 00:03:19.520 align:middle line:90%
and you can't say they haven't.

00:03:19.520 --> 00:03:21.520 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: When I was a
kid, I'd go to the doctor,

00:03:21.520 --> 00:03:24.210 align:middle line:84%
and they'd give me a
little blood pressure test.

00:03:24.210 --> 00:03:28.390 align:middle line:84%
All the time, I would be off
the charts-- off the charts.

00:03:28.390 --> 00:03:30.730 align:middle line:84%
And for a while, they
thought, oh, my God, what's

00:03:30.730 --> 00:03:31.670 align:middle line:90%
wrong with this kid?

00:03:31.670 --> 00:03:32.567 align:middle line:90%
Is he sick?

00:03:32.567 --> 00:03:33.525 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: That's right.

00:03:33.525 --> 00:03:38.020 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And they decided that
there is a symptom that is

00:03:38.020 --> 00:03:38.520 align:middle line:90%
called--

00:03:38.520 --> 00:03:39.060 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: White coat.

00:03:39.060 --> 00:03:39.650 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yup.

00:03:39.650 --> 00:03:43.850 align:middle line:84%
You walk into an office, you
just go right through the roof.

00:03:43.850 --> 00:03:46.370 align:middle line:84%
And after a while,
you calm down,

00:03:46.370 --> 00:03:49.400 align:middle line:84%
they give it to you again,
and then maybe the third time,

00:03:49.400 --> 00:03:50.900 align:middle line:90%
and then you're normal.

00:03:50.900 --> 00:03:53.460 align:middle line:84%
And I would guess that's
the same with somebody who's

00:03:53.460 --> 00:03:57.670 align:middle line:84%
innocent, telling the
truth, but you wire him up,

00:03:57.670 --> 00:03:59.250 align:middle line:90%
it's just-- choom.

00:03:59.250 --> 00:04:01.149 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Well, and
think about it this way.

00:04:01.149 --> 00:04:02.940 align:middle line:84%
When you go to your
doctor, and by the way,

00:04:02.940 --> 00:04:05.100 align:middle line:84%
they don't wear white coats
anymore for that reason.

00:04:05.100 --> 00:04:06.099 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: No, they don't.

00:04:06.099 --> 00:04:06.730 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

00:04:06.730 --> 00:04:08.560 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: But when
you go to your doctor,

00:04:08.560 --> 00:04:14.280 align:middle line:84%
he's just running a test to see
if you're well or maybe what's

00:04:14.280 --> 00:04:17.300 align:middle line:84%
behind the symptoms that
you're manifesting, OK?

00:04:17.300 --> 00:04:20.530 align:middle line:84%
But you can just go
in for a physical

00:04:20.530 --> 00:04:24.610 align:middle line:84%
to play sports and
be nervous about it.

00:04:24.610 --> 00:04:28.320 align:middle line:84%
Imagine, now, how much
amplified that is when you go in

00:04:28.320 --> 00:04:31.720 align:middle line:84%
to take a lie detection
test because perhaps you're

00:04:31.720 --> 00:04:35.960 align:middle line:84%
a suspect in a crime
that could lock you away.

00:04:35.960 --> 00:04:39.612 align:middle line:84%
They put handcuffs on
you and take you to jail.

00:04:39.612 --> 00:04:40.820 align:middle line:90%
Your kids see that happening.

00:04:40.820 --> 00:04:42.120 align:middle line:90%


00:04:42.120 --> 00:04:43.690 align:middle line:90%
So there's a tremendous--

00:04:43.690 --> 00:04:50.600 align:middle line:84%
And then you also have the
perpetrator who schools himself

00:04:50.600 --> 00:04:52.000 align:middle line:90%
in countermeasures.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:54.940 align:middle line:84%
John DeLorean's
lie detection test,

00:04:54.940 --> 00:04:59.170 align:middle line:84%
among lie detection examiners,
is a perfect example of this.

00:04:59.170 --> 00:05:02.800 align:middle line:84%
You see him moving,
and he won't sit still.

00:05:02.800 --> 00:05:04.435 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Was he doing
that on purpose?

00:05:04.435 --> 00:05:05.310 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: Absolutely.

00:05:05.310 --> 00:05:06.559 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Somebody trained him.

00:05:06.559 --> 00:05:07.730 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: Yeah, absolutely.

00:05:07.730 --> 00:05:11.940 align:middle line:84%
He had been prepared to take
that lie detection test.

00:05:11.940 --> 00:05:13.810 align:middle line:84%
And when it was given
to him, David Raskin,

00:05:13.810 --> 00:05:17.510 align:middle line:84%
University of Utah, conducted
the test I'm talking about.

00:05:17.510 --> 00:05:22.100 align:middle line:84%
He, too, passed the test,
or it was inconclusive.

00:05:22.100 --> 00:05:24.670 align:middle line:84%
You couldn't say he was
practicing deception

00:05:24.670 --> 00:05:25.560 align:middle line:90%
on the basis of it.

00:05:25.560 --> 00:05:28.500 align:middle line:84%
But if you can't get somebody
to sit still, it's irrelevant.

00:05:28.500 --> 00:05:30.130 align:middle line:90%
That's a whole other story.

00:05:30.130 --> 00:05:32.000 align:middle line:90%
Bottom line is this.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:36.030 align:middle line:84%
I thought if I could
use this information

00:05:36.030 --> 00:05:39.930 align:middle line:84%
to minimize the impact
of inconclusives,

00:05:39.930 --> 00:05:43.670 align:middle line:84%
if I could do away
with inconclusives,

00:05:43.670 --> 00:05:46.237 align:middle line:84%
my agency would be at
the top of the charts.

00:05:46.237 --> 00:05:46.820 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Huge.

00:05:46.820 --> 00:05:47.486 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: Right.

00:05:47.486 --> 00:05:51.060 align:middle line:84%
So I went to work on
finding everything

00:05:51.060 --> 00:05:54.050 align:middle line:84%
that I could find about
subliminal communication.

00:05:54.050 --> 00:05:56.610 align:middle line:84%
How did they do it,
da-da-da, da-da-da-da.

00:05:56.610 --> 00:06:00.110 align:middle line:84%
Make a long story short, I
bought all the audiotapes

00:06:00.110 --> 00:06:01.735 align:middle line:84%
that were out there
on the marketplace.

00:06:01.735 --> 00:06:02.985 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Everything out there.

00:06:02.985 --> 00:06:05.294 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Yeah, because I
called them on the phone.

00:06:05.294 --> 00:06:07.960 align:middle line:84%
I had called these manufacturers
and said, "how do you do this?"

00:06:07.960 --> 00:06:10.187 align:middle line:84%
And you'd think I was
asking for the secret recipe

00:06:10.187 --> 00:06:10.770 align:middle line:90%
for Coca-Cola.

00:06:10.770 --> 00:06:11.395 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right.

00:06:11.395 --> 00:06:13.230 align:middle line:84%
And they deny it,
first of all, right?

00:06:13.230 --> 00:06:14.830 align:middle line:90%
We don't do this stuff.

00:06:14.830 --> 00:06:18.070 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Well, the people
I was calling actually

00:06:18.070 --> 00:06:19.622 align:middle line:84%
claimed to make
subliminal programs.

00:06:19.622 --> 00:06:21.080 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: They made
this, all right.

00:06:21.080 --> 00:06:22.663 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: So I bought
all these tapes,

00:06:22.663 --> 00:06:25.040 align:middle line:84%
and I sent them to audio
forensic laboratories.

00:06:25.040 --> 00:06:26.360 align:middle line:90%
And I said, what's on these?

00:06:26.360 --> 00:06:26.730 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Where's the message?

00:06:26.730 --> 00:06:27.715 align:middle line:90%
How are they doing this?

00:06:27.715 --> 00:06:28.340 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: Yeah.

00:06:28.340 --> 00:06:29.880 align:middle line:90%
Well, I get this phone call.

00:06:29.880 --> 00:06:33.750 align:middle line:84%
It says, Eldon, there's
nothing on these.

00:06:33.750 --> 00:06:35.940 align:middle line:84%
We have stripped it off,
whatever they've done.

00:06:35.940 --> 00:06:39.756 align:middle line:84%
Well, I subsequently
learned that, most of,

00:06:39.756 --> 00:06:42.490 align:middle line:84%
every one of these
tapes, they bury

00:06:42.490 --> 00:06:45.530 align:middle line:84%
it 50, 60 dB beneath
the primary carrier.

00:06:45.530 --> 00:06:46.920 align:middle line:90%
So you don't really get it out.

00:06:46.920 --> 00:06:47.210 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: You can't pull it out.

00:06:47.210 --> 00:06:47.730 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: No, it's not there.

00:06:47.730 --> 00:06:49.600 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But does the
human mind pull it out?

00:06:49.600 --> 00:06:50.660 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: No, not
at that level, no.

00:06:50.660 --> 00:06:51.451 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: I see, OK.

00:06:51.451 --> 00:06:53.310 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: No, you
have to have a signal

00:06:53.310 --> 00:06:55.675 align:middle line:84%
strength sufficient to
cause the neuron to fire,

00:06:55.675 --> 00:06:58.560 align:middle line:84%
or you're not going to
process any information.

00:06:58.560 --> 00:07:01.520 align:middle line:84%
So at any rate,
I then set about,

00:07:01.520 --> 00:07:04.040 align:middle line:90%
what hard evidence is there?

00:07:04.040 --> 00:07:07.450 align:middle line:84%
And we went to the
university library.

00:07:07.450 --> 00:07:10.340 align:middle line:84%
We pulled all the psych
and med abstracts.

00:07:10.340 --> 00:07:14.260 align:middle line:84%
We ended up
developing a mast way

00:07:14.260 --> 00:07:20.230 align:middle line:84%
to deliver information that
bypasses critical awareness.

00:07:20.230 --> 00:07:23.880 align:middle line:84%
And then we took this back to
the lie detection scenario.

00:07:23.880 --> 00:07:28.360 align:middle line:84%
Not only did it end
inconclusives almost virtually,

00:07:28.360 --> 00:07:31.020 align:middle line:84%
but the confession
rate, George--

00:07:31.020 --> 00:07:33.920 align:middle line:84%
we were dealing with just
some simple messages that

00:07:33.920 --> 00:07:39.440 align:middle line:84%
'truth shall set you
free', simple messages.

00:07:39.440 --> 00:07:43.990 align:middle line:84%
Honestly, and I know
you'll never be,

00:07:43.990 --> 00:07:47.040 align:middle line:84%
but if you're ever in
a situation like that,

00:07:47.040 --> 00:07:50.025 align:middle line:84%
interrogations don't get serious
in the first three hours.

00:07:50.025 --> 00:07:51.400 align:middle line:84%
You just kind of
cool your heels.

00:07:51.400 --> 00:07:54.570 align:middle line:84%
Because everybody knows you're
not going to get a confession.

00:07:54.570 --> 00:07:58.150 align:middle line:84%
So it's after that
first three hours

00:07:58.150 --> 00:08:01.296 align:middle line:84%
that the interrogations
start heating up.

00:08:01.296 --> 00:08:04.060 align:middle line:84%
I was getting
confessions so rapidly it

00:08:04.060 --> 00:08:06.395 align:middle line:84%
was almost like I wanted
to say, whoa, wait,

00:08:06.395 --> 00:08:07.709 align:middle line:90%
I'm paid by the hour.

00:08:07.709 --> 00:08:09.500 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Have you gotten
the point, though,

00:08:09.500 --> 00:08:14.510 align:middle line:84%
that the guilty person wanted
to take a lie detector test just

00:08:14.510 --> 00:08:17.526 align:middle line:84%
to prove that he wasn't
guilty even though he was?

00:08:17.526 --> 00:08:18.790 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: Oh, yes.

00:08:18.790 --> 00:08:24.155 align:middle line:84%
You have those overconfident,
sometimes sociopathic people.

00:08:24.155 --> 00:08:26.446 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Because they figure
they have nothing to lose,

00:08:26.446 --> 00:08:26.510 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:08:26.510 --> 00:08:28.560 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Yeah, I
mean, "I'll volunteer

00:08:28.560 --> 00:08:32.950 align:middle line:84%
to take a lie detection test"
is evidence in their minds

00:08:32.950 --> 00:08:34.742 align:middle line:84%
a priori that they
didn't commit the crime.

00:08:34.742 --> 00:08:36.158 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: They
didn't do it, right?

00:08:36.158 --> 00:08:36.830 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: Right.

00:08:36.830 --> 00:08:40.440 align:middle line:84%
It becomes, well, why
would I have volunteered

00:08:40.440 --> 00:08:42.530 align:middle line:90%
if they failed the test, see?

00:08:42.530 --> 00:08:46.230 align:middle line:84%
So it can become all
a part of their alibi.

00:08:46.230 --> 00:08:50.020 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Now, are these
tests admissible or not?

00:08:50.020 --> 00:08:52.020 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: They can be
admissible by stipulation.

00:08:52.020 --> 00:08:54.870 align:middle line:90%


00:08:54.870 --> 00:08:58.310 align:middle line:84%
The real art of lie
detection, which is really

00:08:58.310 --> 00:09:01.190 align:middle line:84%
what we're here to talk
about, but the real art of lie

00:09:01.190 --> 00:09:04.130 align:middle line:84%
detection is not
in the equipment.

00:09:04.130 --> 00:09:05.005 align:middle line:90%
It's in the examiner.

00:09:05.005 --> 00:09:06.296 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: How they interpret it.

00:09:06.296 --> 00:09:08.880 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Your equipment is
just sophisticated biofeedback,

00:09:08.880 --> 00:09:11.250 align:middle line:90%
that's all.

00:09:11.250 --> 00:09:16.670 align:middle line:84%
It's what follows the lie
detection examination that

00:09:16.670 --> 00:09:18.740 align:middle line:90%
leads to its real merit.

00:09:18.740 --> 00:09:19.764 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Fascinating.

00:09:19.764 --> 00:09:21.555 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: But during
the interview process,

00:09:21.555 --> 00:09:27.170 align:middle line:84%
there's an unbelievable amount
of uncovering that goes on.

00:09:27.170 --> 00:09:30.540 align:middle line:84%
You and I-- if I were to say
to you, OK, George, today

00:09:30.540 --> 00:09:33.490 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to ask you
a couple of questions

00:09:33.490 --> 00:09:35.700 align:middle line:84%
that we'll use in a
zone of comparison

00:09:35.700 --> 00:09:38.170 align:middle line:84%
to just be sure you're
telling me the truth.

00:09:38.170 --> 00:09:41.575 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to ask
you, did you ever

00:09:41.575 --> 00:09:43.090 align:middle line:90%
lie to someone that trusted you?

00:09:43.090 --> 00:09:44.290 align:middle line:90%
You're not a liar, are you?

00:09:44.290 --> 00:09:47.410 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: No, I didn't lie on
purpose, not to hurt them.

00:09:47.410 --> 00:09:48.710 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: Well, we know, right?

00:09:48.710 --> 00:09:49.160 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah. [LAUGHS]

00:09:49.160 --> 00:09:51.076 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: So we know
that that's a forced lie.

00:09:51.076 --> 00:09:54.220 align:middle line:84%
We know there's no such thing
as somebody who didn't lie

00:09:54.220 --> 00:09:55.490 align:middle line:90%
to somebody that trusted them.

00:09:55.490 --> 00:09:57.020 align:middle line:84%
Or I'm going to
say to you, did you

00:09:57.020 --> 00:09:58.364 align:middle line:90%
ever steal anything, George?

00:09:58.364 --> 00:09:59.530 align:middle line:90%
You're not a thief, are you?

00:09:59.530 --> 00:10:01.071 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Once when
I was a little boy

00:10:01.071 --> 00:10:03.560 align:middle line:84%
and I didn't think
I was stealing,

00:10:03.560 --> 00:10:06.990 align:middle line:84%
there were some little
pocket knives down

00:10:06.990 --> 00:10:10.440 align:middle line:84%
on the floor next to a
cash register as if they

00:10:10.440 --> 00:10:13.280 align:middle line:90%
were in the garbage or rubbish.

00:10:13.280 --> 00:10:15.870 align:middle line:90%
I was 10 years old.

00:10:15.870 --> 00:10:20.680 align:middle line:84%
I reached down in the dust and
the rubble and took it home.

00:10:20.680 --> 00:10:23.390 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: OK, but today you
recognize that was wrong.

00:10:23.390 --> 00:10:25.680 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: My mother
made me take it back.

00:10:25.680 --> 00:10:27.805 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Oh, that was nice
of you to take it back.

00:10:27.805 --> 00:10:29.700 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But I didn't
do it to steal it.

00:10:29.700 --> 00:10:30.186 align:middle line:84%
I thought it was
being thrown out.

00:10:30.186 --> 00:10:32.269 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: When I asked
this question to you today,

00:10:32.269 --> 00:10:35.900 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to say, other than
that pocket knife, George,

00:10:35.900 --> 00:10:37.900 align:middle line:84%
you've never stolen
anything, have you?

00:10:37.900 --> 00:10:38.621 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Correct.

00:10:38.621 --> 00:10:40.120 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: And the
fact of the matter

00:10:40.120 --> 00:10:42.251 align:middle line:84%
is that you and I both
know that's not true.

00:10:42.251 --> 00:10:43.750 align:middle line:84%
I don't mean to put
you on the spot.

00:10:43.750 --> 00:10:44.280 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: No, I haven't.

00:10:44.280 --> 00:10:45.821 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: No doubt
you took something

00:10:45.821 --> 00:10:47.222 align:middle line:84%
from your parents
or your brother

00:10:47.222 --> 00:10:48.930 align:middle line:84%
or a pencil from the
place that you work.

00:10:48.930 --> 00:10:50.020 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: No, sir.

00:10:50.020 --> 00:10:50.812 align:middle line:90%
No, sir.

00:10:50.812 --> 00:10:52.970 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: [LAUGHS]

00:10:52.970 --> 00:10:55.534 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But it is a
part of mind programming.

00:10:55.534 --> 00:10:56.200 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: It is.

00:10:56.200 --> 00:10:57.366 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: People can do that.

00:10:57.366 --> 00:11:01.240 align:middle line:84%
So let's get into the
basis of why they do this.

00:11:01.240 --> 00:11:02.540 align:middle line:90%
And who does it?

00:11:02.540 --> 00:11:07.637 align:middle line:84%
Government, industry, stores--
who's mind programming us?

00:11:07.637 --> 00:11:08.470 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: Everybody.

00:11:08.470 --> 00:11:14.470 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I think that the
greatest misconception today is

00:11:14.470 --> 00:11:18.820 align:middle line:84%
that I make my own choices,
that I am an informed person,

00:11:18.820 --> 00:11:22.430 align:middle line:84%
and I can decide what
I want to decide.

00:11:22.430 --> 00:11:28.800 align:middle line:84%
We live in a society where--
by now trillions of dollars--

00:11:28.800 --> 00:11:33.050 align:middle line:84%
in the '80s it was a $10 billion
a year, the estimate that

00:11:33.050 --> 00:11:36.170 align:middle line:84%
was spent by industry
and government

00:11:36.170 --> 00:11:39.090 align:middle line:84%
on learning to plumb
your subconscious,

00:11:39.090 --> 00:11:42.380 align:middle line:84%
learning to motivate
you, control you.

00:11:42.380 --> 00:11:47.440 align:middle line:84%
Our mandatory educational system
is a copy of a Prussian 1812

00:11:47.440 --> 00:11:52.120 align:middle line:84%
system that Dewey and
Thorndike both said

00:11:52.120 --> 00:11:56.780 align:middle line:84%
essentially existed to teach
you to be a good citizen,

00:11:56.780 --> 00:12:00.790 align:middle line:84%
to think in a certain way, to
give you the alternatives that

00:12:00.790 --> 00:12:03.860 align:middle line:90%
were the appropriate decisions.

00:12:03.860 --> 00:12:08.460 align:middle line:84%
We didn't look at the
history of this country.

00:12:08.460 --> 00:12:11.650 align:middle line:10%
And we have to go to a man
by the name of Edward Bernays

00:12:11.650 --> 00:12:12.610 align:middle line:10%
when we look at--

00:12:12.610 --> 00:12:14.270 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Mr. Public
Relations, right?

00:12:14.270 --> 00:12:15.300 align:middle line:10%
He was the first--

00:12:15.300 --> 00:12:19.610 align:middle line:10%
>>TAYLOR: Yeah, the father of
what today we call propaganda.

00:12:19.610 --> 00:12:21.910 align:middle line:84%
In his famous book,
"Propaganda," he

00:12:21.910 --> 00:12:25.960 align:middle line:84%
said it's the duty of
the elite to orchestrate

00:12:25.960 --> 00:12:29.370 align:middle line:84%
the understanding of
the masses in order

00:12:29.370 --> 00:12:31.790 align:middle line:90%
to have a cohesive society.

00:12:31.790 --> 00:12:33.920 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What year was
he around doing this?

00:12:33.920 --> 00:12:37.390 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Well, Bernays was
a nephew of Sigmund Freud.

00:12:37.390 --> 00:12:39.085 align:middle line:90%
And he saw what Freud did.

00:12:39.085 --> 00:12:43.000 align:middle line:84%
And he said, hey, there's
a real opportunity here,

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:47.000 align:middle line:84%
not for purposes
of healing someone

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:49.110 align:middle line:90%
but for purposes of controlling.

00:12:49.110 --> 00:12:50.220 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Manipulation.

00:12:50.220 --> 00:12:50.845 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: Yeah.

00:12:50.845 --> 00:12:54.790 align:middle line:84%
And so he advised
President Woodrow Wilson.

00:12:54.790 --> 00:12:59.640 align:middle line:84%
I mean, we're talking the
turn of the 20th century,

00:12:59.640 --> 00:13:01.860 align:middle line:90%
early 1900s.

00:13:01.860 --> 00:13:08.360 align:middle line:84%
He was involved in government
takeovers in South America,

00:13:08.360 --> 00:13:13.490 align:middle line:84%
supporting companies
like the food industry.

00:13:13.490 --> 00:13:17.430 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Do you think Hitler
watched what he did or maybe

00:13:17.430 --> 00:13:18.590 align:middle line:90%
even read what he did?

00:13:18.590 --> 00:13:20.227 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Well, we
know that Goebbels--

00:13:20.227 --> 00:13:21.560 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Minister of Propaganda.

00:13:21.560 --> 00:13:24.580 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: Yeah, he ate it up.

00:13:24.580 --> 00:13:25.580 align:middle line:90%
He was a hero.

00:13:25.580 --> 00:13:28.430 align:middle line:84%
I mean, Bernays
was Goebbels' hero.

00:13:28.430 --> 00:13:32.850 align:middle line:84%
So there's no doubt
about that whatsoever.

00:13:32.850 --> 00:13:34.800 align:middle line:84%
And what we have
to understand is

00:13:34.800 --> 00:13:36.460 align:middle line:84%
Bernays really
fathered something

00:13:36.460 --> 00:13:38.800 align:middle line:90%
we call scientific marketing.

00:13:38.800 --> 00:13:42.340 align:middle line:84%
But the scientific
marketing of those days,

00:13:42.340 --> 00:13:47.920 align:middle line:84%
maybe a blood pressure
cuff or a pneumo,

00:13:47.920 --> 00:13:51.480 align:middle line:84%
like a lie detection,
that was designed

00:13:51.480 --> 00:13:55.860 align:middle line:84%
see how you responded
to an ad or to a picture

00:13:55.860 --> 00:13:59.990 align:middle line:84%
in order to be able to
present something to you

00:13:59.990 --> 00:14:02.490 align:middle line:90%
that stimulated you, all right?

00:14:02.490 --> 00:14:04.990 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And then they went
into the galvanic skin response.

00:14:04.990 --> 00:14:06.710 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Yeah, they
used GSR all the time.

00:14:06.710 --> 00:14:09.001 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And now what they
have going-- listen to this.

00:14:09.001 --> 00:14:11.170 align:middle line:84%
And you're probably
aware of this.

00:14:11.170 --> 00:14:14.780 align:middle line:84%
They have eye tracking,
where they test you,

00:14:14.780 --> 00:14:18.790 align:middle line:84%
and they'll play a commercial
to a group of people

00:14:18.790 --> 00:14:22.550 align:middle line:84%
that this test tracks
their eye movements.

00:14:22.550 --> 00:14:25.880 align:middle line:84%
So a car comes out
with a gorgeous woman.

00:14:25.880 --> 00:14:28.350 align:middle line:84%
They want to know, what
is the guy looking at?

00:14:28.350 --> 00:14:30.070 align:middle line:90%
Is he looking at the car?

00:14:30.070 --> 00:14:31.530 align:middle line:90%
Is he looking at the woman?

00:14:31.530 --> 00:14:34.160 align:middle line:84%
What is that mind
really trying to do?

00:14:34.160 --> 00:14:36.130 align:middle line:84%
And they get their
data that way.

00:14:36.130 --> 00:14:39.100 align:middle line:84%
And they realize the guy's
looking at the woman, not

00:14:39.100 --> 00:14:40.000 align:middle line:90%
the car.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:43.310 align:middle line:84%
And so they know how to do their
commercials based around that.

00:14:43.310 --> 00:14:44.380 align:middle line:90%
It's amazing.

00:14:44.380 --> 00:14:46.660 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: It goes even
further than that.

00:14:46.660 --> 00:14:50.030 align:middle line:84%
A friend of mine in Mexico
is using that technology

00:14:50.030 --> 00:14:51.730 align:middle line:90%
right now.

00:14:51.730 --> 00:14:54.710 align:middle line:84%
And of course, it was
developed here in America.

00:14:54.710 --> 00:14:57.110 align:middle line:90%
But here's how far it goes.

00:14:57.110 --> 00:15:01.330 align:middle line:84%
FMRI, Functional Magnetic
Resonance Imaging,

00:15:01.330 --> 00:15:04.790 align:middle line:84%
gives us the ability to
watch the brain live-time.

00:15:04.790 --> 00:15:08.480 align:middle line:84%
So we can see how the
brain responds to stimulus.

00:15:08.480 --> 00:15:13.720 align:middle line:84%
OK, we know that if you
show a cigarette smoker,

00:15:13.720 --> 00:15:17.940 align:middle line:84%
the Surgeon General's warning
on a pack of cigarettes,

00:15:17.940 --> 00:15:22.120 align:middle line:84%
that the reward center in
the brain becomes excited.

00:15:22.120 --> 00:15:25.460 align:middle line:84%
It causes him to
want to smoke more.

00:15:25.460 --> 00:15:26.564 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That slogan?

00:15:26.564 --> 00:15:27.480 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: That slogan.

00:15:27.480 --> 00:15:29.730 align:middle line:90%
So they make it larger, bolder.

00:15:29.730 --> 00:15:30.390 align:middle line:90%
Think about it.

00:15:30.390 --> 00:15:31.830 align:middle line:84%
Originally it was a
small, black thing.

00:15:31.830 --> 00:15:33.200 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You would think
it would scare them away.

00:15:33.200 --> 00:15:33.742 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't...

00:15:33.742 --> 00:15:34.949 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: But it doesn't, no.

00:15:34.949 --> 00:15:36.180 align:middle line:90%
It has the opposite effect.

00:15:36.180 --> 00:15:39.660 align:middle line:84%
So by using all
of these sciences,

00:15:39.660 --> 00:15:43.860 align:middle line:84%
we've come to understand how to
motivate people to do things.

00:15:43.860 --> 00:15:49.050 align:middle line:84%
George, you talked about
the car and a girl.

00:15:49.050 --> 00:15:53.320 align:middle line:84%
We know that one study,
and there are many,

00:15:53.320 --> 00:15:56.430 align:middle line:84%
but one study
paired an automobile

00:15:56.430 --> 00:16:00.120 align:middle line:84%
with a beautiful woman
scantily dressed-- bikini, OK?

00:16:00.120 --> 00:16:03.310 align:middle line:84%
And men in the study
were asked to rate

00:16:03.310 --> 00:16:06.050 align:middle line:90%
the speeds of the automobiles.

00:16:06.050 --> 00:16:08.490 align:middle line:84%
They always rated the one
with the beautiful woman

00:16:08.490 --> 00:16:10.085 align:middle line:90%
as being the fastest.

00:16:10.085 --> 00:16:14.150 align:middle line:84%
Now, they were brought back a
week later-- same automobiles,

00:16:14.150 --> 00:16:16.340 align:middle line:90%
different colors, mixed up.

00:16:16.340 --> 00:16:18.360 align:middle line:90%
She was on a different car.

00:16:18.360 --> 00:16:20.940 align:middle line:84%
Again, they rated the
automobile that she

00:16:20.940 --> 00:16:23.690 align:middle line:90%
