And his comment was, whenever
we're dealing with stimulus

00:19:58.830 --> 00:20:03.260 align:middle line:84%
that we don't understand, it
produces anxiety, keeps us

00:20:03.260 --> 00:20:05.380 align:middle line:84%
in a heightened
state of arousal.

00:20:05.380 --> 00:20:08.480 align:middle line:84%
It will lead to
manifesting symptoms that

00:20:08.480 --> 00:20:11.940 align:middle line:90%
are psychological in nature.

00:20:11.940 --> 00:20:16.900 align:middle line:84%
So we live in a time that
our threshold of arousal

00:20:16.900 --> 00:20:22.450 align:middle line:84%
is such that we're all
basically inundated 24/7

00:20:22.450 --> 00:20:26.120 align:middle line:84%
with so much information
that we're on a verge.

00:20:26.120 --> 00:20:30.480 align:middle line:84%
And most of this
stimulus is unrecognized.

00:20:30.480 --> 00:20:35.900 align:middle line:84%
And because it's unrecognized,
we try to sort it out.

00:20:35.900 --> 00:20:38.370 align:middle line:84%
We try to decide,
well, what is it?

00:20:38.370 --> 00:20:39.670 align:middle line:90%
Why am I feeling this way?

00:20:39.670 --> 00:20:41.260 align:middle line:90%
What has me on edge?

00:20:41.260 --> 00:20:45.410 align:middle line:84%
And we see all kinds of
ways that that's acted out.

00:20:45.410 --> 00:20:48.520 align:middle line:84%
And many of them are
just simply not healthy.

00:20:48.520 --> 00:20:52.070 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: During the tragedy
of 9/11 back in 2001,

00:20:52.070 --> 00:20:56.740 align:middle line:84%
they came out with a color
scheme, a coded color scheme,

00:20:56.740 --> 00:21:01.500 align:middle line:84%
to tell you how bad the next
terrorist possibility would be.

00:21:01.500 --> 00:21:02.640 align:middle line:90%
I hated that.

00:21:02.640 --> 00:21:04.120 align:middle line:90%
I thought it was manipulation.

00:21:04.120 --> 00:21:07.110 align:middle line:84%
I thought it was fear-mongering,
where they would change

00:21:07.110 --> 00:21:11.750 align:middle line:84%
their colors, and the closer you
got to red, the more dangerous

00:21:11.750 --> 00:21:12.710 align:middle line:90%
it was going to be.

00:21:12.710 --> 00:21:15.280 align:middle line:84%
They've subsequently
stopped that.

00:21:15.280 --> 00:21:17.960 align:middle line:84%
I've always wondered
what happened

00:21:17.960 --> 00:21:19.450 align:middle line:90%
to have them stop that.

00:21:19.450 --> 00:21:22.750 align:middle line:84%
I know why they started it, of
course, to keep us all on edge.

00:21:22.750 --> 00:21:23.650 align:middle line:90%
Something happened.

00:21:23.650 --> 00:21:26.120 align:middle line:84%
Somebody told them,
"don't do this anymore."

00:21:26.120 --> 00:21:27.139 align:middle line:90%
What happened?

00:21:27.139 --> 00:21:28.430 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: I don't know, George.

00:21:28.430 --> 00:21:30.180 align:middle line:10%
The answer is, I don't know.

00:21:30.180 --> 00:21:31.570 align:middle line:10%
There are many possibilities.

00:21:31.570 --> 00:21:34.450 align:middle line:10%
I think essentially
my take on that

00:21:34.450 --> 00:21:36.330 align:middle line:10%
is it had served its purpose.

00:21:36.330 --> 00:21:39.690 align:middle line:84%
We gave away a whole
lot of our rights

00:21:39.690 --> 00:21:43.764 align:middle line:90%
in this country due to that.

00:21:43.764 --> 00:21:45.180 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Was it
great programming?

00:21:45.180 --> 00:21:46.390 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: Yeah, I believe so.

00:21:46.390 --> 00:21:48.320 align:middle line:90%
I absolutely believe so.

00:21:48.320 --> 00:21:51.010 align:middle line:84%
Let's contrast it
with something.

00:21:51.010 --> 00:21:54.049 align:middle line:84%
You remember David Koresh in
Waco, Texas, Janet Napolitano.

00:21:54.049 --> 00:21:54.840 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: I sure do.

00:21:54.840 --> 00:21:59.760 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: OK,
during Desert Storm,

00:21:59.760 --> 00:22:03.380 align:middle line:84%
Operation Solo would
take frequencies--

00:22:03.380 --> 00:22:10.160 align:middle line:84%
we think of these frequencies as
being in the infra-sound area,

00:22:10.160 --> 00:22:13.420 align:middle line:90%
like 20 to 24 Hertz base.

00:22:13.420 --> 00:22:18.540 align:middle line:84%
We don't hear them,
but we process them.

00:22:18.540 --> 00:22:21.120 align:middle line:84%
And what happens when
we process them is

00:22:21.120 --> 00:22:24.030 align:middle line:90%
they create a level of anxiety.

00:22:24.030 --> 00:22:27.100 align:middle line:84%
They make us feel anxious,
like something bad is

00:22:27.100 --> 00:22:28.570 align:middle line:90%
about to happen.

00:22:28.570 --> 00:22:35.230 align:middle line:84%
And a continued delivery of this
can cause nervous breakdowns.

00:22:35.230 --> 00:22:41.370 align:middle line:84%
So during Desert Storm, we
pumped these frequencies on top

00:22:41.370 --> 00:22:43.350 align:middle line:84%
of, piggybacked
them if you will,

00:22:43.350 --> 00:22:45.780 align:middle line:90%
on top of normal broadcasts.

00:22:45.780 --> 00:22:48.720 align:middle line:84%
And many people say
that was a good deal

00:22:48.720 --> 00:22:53.810 align:middle line:84%
of the reason behind why so
many of the Republican Guard

00:22:53.810 --> 00:22:58.130 align:middle line:84%
just surrendered, just put down
their weapons and walked in.

00:22:58.130 --> 00:23:04.180 align:middle line:84%
OK, David Koresh--
Soviet advisers--

00:23:04.180 --> 00:23:05.820 align:middle line:84%
and I know this from
Shelia Ostrander,

00:23:05.820 --> 00:23:08.460 align:middle line:90%
author of "Superlearning."

00:23:08.460 --> 00:23:10.140 align:middle line:90%
She sent me information.

00:23:10.140 --> 00:23:12.080 align:middle line:90%
We'd correspond and talk.

00:23:12.080 --> 00:23:16.240 align:middle line:84%
Soviet advisers told
our people, don't

00:23:16.240 --> 00:23:19.650 align:middle line:90%
do this in the Waco situation.

00:23:19.650 --> 00:23:21.420 align:middle line:90%
We don't know what could happen.

00:23:21.420 --> 00:23:29.100 align:middle line:84%
If you take these Tibetan
mantras and then piggyback

00:23:29.100 --> 00:23:31.950 align:middle line:84%
these frequencies on them,
anything could happen.

00:23:31.950 --> 00:23:33.740 align:middle line:90%
It could become very explosive.

00:23:33.740 --> 00:23:36.560 align:middle line:84%
They're not necessarily going
to-- well, he did it anyway.

00:23:36.560 --> 00:23:39.664 align:middle line:84%
We ran trucks, sound
trucks around the facility.

00:23:39.664 --> 00:23:40.580 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: The compound.

00:23:40.580 --> 00:23:43.170 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: That's right,
the compound doings.

00:23:43.170 --> 00:23:45.030 align:middle line:90%
So everybody knows what happens.

00:23:45.030 --> 00:23:47.210 align:middle line:84%
I mean, all that
anxiety built up,

00:23:47.210 --> 00:23:50.250 align:middle line:84%
and suddenly there was a
shootout, an explosion.

00:23:50.250 --> 00:23:54.132 align:middle line:90%
And we provoked that.

00:23:54.132 --> 00:23:55.590 align:middle line:84%
What would have
happened otherwise?

00:23:55.590 --> 00:23:56.560 align:middle line:90%
I don't know.

00:23:56.560 --> 00:24:00.090 align:middle line:84%
But it's easy to look in
20/20 hindsight and see

00:24:00.090 --> 00:24:03.434 align:middle line:84%
that the Soviets, who worked
a lot with this technology,

00:24:03.434 --> 00:24:05.460 align:middle line:90%
in fact--

00:24:05.460 --> 00:24:06.540 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: They knew.

00:24:06.540 --> 00:24:09.260 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Carl Schleicher,
the late Carl Schleicher,

00:24:09.260 --> 00:24:14.710 align:middle line:84%
who was the founder of Mankind
Research-- Mankind is still

00:24:14.710 --> 00:24:16.820 align:middle line:84%
involved in some of
this kind of thing--

00:24:16.820 --> 00:24:22.330 align:middle line:84%
told me the Soviets were
using it during the Cold War.

00:24:22.330 --> 00:24:26.780 align:middle line:84%
They were pumping this
information on our embassy,

00:24:26.780 --> 00:24:29.560 align:middle line:84%
and that's why we had
so many ambassadors

00:24:29.560 --> 00:24:33.430 align:middle line:84%
that we lost over there
due to physical conditions.

00:24:33.430 --> 00:24:36.340 align:middle line:84%
I mean, they would
become very ill.

00:24:36.340 --> 00:24:37.340 align:middle line:90%
We had to pull them out.

00:24:37.340 --> 00:24:39.560 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's amazing, though.

00:24:39.560 --> 00:24:42.630 align:middle line:84%
Mind programming--
when you go to a store,

00:24:42.630 --> 00:24:44.340 align:middle line:90%
are they manipulating us?

00:24:44.340 --> 00:24:47.220 align:middle line:84%
You remember they used to talk
about the Blue Light Special,

00:24:47.220 --> 00:24:49.540 align:middle line:84%
but is there something
else going on when

00:24:49.540 --> 00:24:51.830 align:middle line:90%
you walk into a store or not?

00:24:51.830 --> 00:24:56.260 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Well, the answer
to that is yes, yes, and yes.

00:24:56.260 --> 00:24:59.050 align:middle line:84%
Marketing is, as you've
already pointed out,

00:24:59.050 --> 00:25:01.720 align:middle line:90%
very sophisticated today.

00:25:01.720 --> 00:25:04.900 align:middle line:84%
Product placement is a
critical aspect of that.

00:25:04.900 --> 00:25:08.150 align:middle line:84%
Color marketing is an
important ingredient.

00:25:08.150 --> 00:25:13.210 align:middle line:84%
But you could also be exposed
to subliminal messages.

00:25:13.210 --> 00:25:18.710 align:middle line:84%
Back in the '80s, I attempted
to get some legislation that

00:25:18.710 --> 00:25:20.860 align:middle line:90%
would require informed consent.

00:25:20.860 --> 00:25:23.200 align:middle line:84%
You remember the
microwave oven when they--

00:25:23.200 --> 00:25:24.822 align:middle line:84%
you were in the
Navy, so you know

00:25:24.822 --> 00:25:28.450 align:middle line:84%
they had microwaves on
submarines way back.

00:25:28.450 --> 00:25:30.750 align:middle line:84%
But when they became
popular in America,

00:25:30.750 --> 00:25:33.690 align:middle line:84%
everyone was concerned
about this microwave energy.

00:25:33.690 --> 00:25:37.060 align:middle line:84%
So if you went into a
restaurant that had a microwave,

00:25:37.060 --> 00:25:40.620 align:middle line:84%
there was a warning decal on the
door, we have a microwave oven.

00:25:40.620 --> 00:25:43.900 align:middle line:84%
OK, well I just wanted
some kind of decal,

00:25:43.900 --> 00:25:48.220 align:middle line:84%
some kind of notification that
if you visited a store and they

00:25:48.220 --> 00:25:54.450 align:middle line:84%
had, quote, "anti-theft"
subliminal messages,

00:25:54.450 --> 00:25:55.800 align:middle line:90%
that they would disclose that.

00:25:55.800 --> 00:25:58.152 align:middle line:84%
Because they'll tell you
that this is anti-theft.

00:25:58.152 --> 00:25:59.610 align:middle line:84%
And there's been
a lot of work that

00:25:59.610 --> 00:26:04.480 align:middle line:84%
shows that anti-theft
subliminal messages are

00:26:04.480 --> 00:26:08.780 align:middle line:84%
capable of lowering
reserve requirements, theft

00:26:08.780 --> 00:26:10.230 align:middle line:90%
in the store, OK?

00:26:10.230 --> 00:26:13.480 align:middle line:84%
The problem with these
anti-theft messages

00:26:13.480 --> 00:26:17.520 align:middle line:84%
is very often they will
be constructed this way,

00:26:17.520 --> 00:26:20.550 align:middle line:90%
buying is honest.

00:26:20.550 --> 00:26:22.480 align:middle line:90%
You want to be honest.

00:26:22.480 --> 00:26:24.230 align:middle line:90%
Now what does that say to you?

00:26:24.230 --> 00:26:25.460 align:middle line:90%
It says buy.

00:26:25.460 --> 00:26:28.040 align:middle line:90%
This is a motivational message.

00:26:28.040 --> 00:26:32.020 align:middle line:84%
Well, we were unsuccessful
with the legislation.

00:26:32.020 --> 00:26:36.570 align:middle line:84%
Virtually the who's who
of the marketing world

00:26:36.570 --> 00:26:39.960 align:middle line:84%
came in to oppose
this legislation.

00:26:39.960 --> 00:26:44.600 align:middle line:84%
And they all said, we
don't do it, and if we did,

00:26:44.600 --> 00:26:45.480 align:middle line:90%
it doesn't work.

00:26:45.480 --> 00:26:48.390 align:middle line:84%
Well, the fact of the matter
is that argument has been since

00:26:48.390 --> 00:26:49.920 align:middle line:90%
dismissed many, many times.

00:26:49.920 --> 00:26:51.300 align:middle line:90%
Of course they do it.

00:26:51.300 --> 00:26:52.630 align:middle line:90%
That's a proven instance.

00:26:52.630 --> 00:26:53.960 align:middle line:90%
And of course, it works.

00:26:53.960 --> 00:26:58.940 align:middle line:84%
There's no question about
that any longer, either.

00:26:58.940 --> 00:27:03.450 align:middle line:84%
The bottom line to this
story, in my view, is this.

00:27:03.450 --> 00:27:06.060 align:middle line:84%
Most people believe
they're protected

00:27:06.060 --> 00:27:08.795 align:middle line:84%
against subliminal messages,
whether on a television

00:27:08.795 --> 00:27:12.970 align:middle line:84%
or in the radio or
in the grocery store.

00:27:12.970 --> 00:27:14.160 align:middle line:90%
And they're really not.

00:27:14.160 --> 00:27:16.120 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Because it's
subliminal. [LAUGHS]

00:27:16.120 --> 00:27:17.530 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: Well, not only that.

00:27:17.530 --> 00:27:19.120 align:middle line:90%
There are no laws.

00:27:19.120 --> 00:27:23.300 align:middle line:84%
There's an FCC codification that
says a station cannot knowingly

00:27:23.300 --> 00:27:26.319 align:middle line:84%
do that without
risking their license.

00:27:26.319 --> 00:27:27.110 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Knowingly.

00:27:27.110 --> 00:27:27.943 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: Knowingly.

00:27:27.943 --> 00:27:30.900 align:middle line:84%
But you remember the
Bush Rats ad, don't you?

00:27:30.900 --> 00:27:31.570 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah.

00:27:31.570 --> 00:27:35.450 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: OK, so here Bush
puts behind Al Gore's head

00:27:35.450 --> 00:27:42.550 align:middle line:84%
"rats" bolded out in a
bold subliminal message

00:27:42.550 --> 00:27:49.230 align:middle line:84%
during the election
between Gore and Bush II.

00:27:49.230 --> 00:27:54.070 align:middle line:84%
That ad has been researched
at Adelphi University

00:27:54.070 --> 00:27:57.550 align:middle line:84%
in mock elections to
see if it would indeed

00:27:57.550 --> 00:27:59.580 align:middle line:90%
affect the outcome of election.

00:27:59.580 --> 00:28:02.190 align:middle line:84%
And there's no doubt
that statistically

00:28:02.190 --> 00:28:04.590 align:middle line:90%
it did impact the election.

00:28:04.590 --> 00:28:09.940 align:middle line:84%
Tennessee is one of the
states where the ad ran more

00:28:09.940 --> 00:28:11.160 align:middle line:90%
than any other place.

00:28:11.160 --> 00:28:12.850 align:middle line:84%
And Tennessee is
Al Gore's state.

00:28:12.850 --> 00:28:15.970 align:middle line:90%
And Al Gore lost his home state.

00:28:15.970 --> 00:28:20.180 align:middle line:84%
OK, now, the DNC, the
Democratic National Committee,

00:28:20.180 --> 00:28:22.540 align:middle line:84%
they've got all
power in the world.

00:28:22.540 --> 00:28:26.860 align:middle line:84%
They went after the Bush
people over this ad.

00:28:26.860 --> 00:28:32.290 align:middle line:84%
First, the Bush people argued
that it didn't exist, OK?

00:28:32.290 --> 00:28:36.060 align:middle line:84%
Then when it's so bold, they
said, well, it was an accident.

00:28:36.060 --> 00:28:38.270 align:middle line:84%
But once you see
it, there's no way

00:28:38.270 --> 00:28:40.050 align:middle line:90%
it could have been an accident.

00:28:40.050 --> 00:28:42.690 align:middle line:84%
So then they finally
admitted to doing it.

00:28:42.690 --> 00:28:45.430 align:middle line:84%
Bush, I think, did a great
job of dismissing it,

00:28:45.430 --> 00:28:48.500 align:middle line:84%
because when asked, he
couldn't pronounce the word.

00:28:48.500 --> 00:28:51.210 align:middle line:90%
Su-- sub-- "sublimi?"

00:28:51.210 --> 00:28:54.045 align:middle line:90%
So everybody laughed at it.

00:28:54.045 --> 00:28:57.030 align:middle line:84%
Bottom line is, when they
were all said and done,

00:28:57.030 --> 00:29:01.430 align:middle line:84%
the DNC was unable to
get anything as a result.

00:29:01.430 --> 00:29:05.770 align:middle line:84%
The station denied knowing
that it had been there.

00:29:05.770 --> 00:29:07.420 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Which is
possible, right?

00:29:07.420 --> 00:29:08.720 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: Of course, of course.

00:29:08.720 --> 00:29:10.710 align:middle line:84%
The ad agency did
it, and there's

00:29:10.710 --> 00:29:13.540 align:middle line:84%
no way to pursue the ad
agency, because it's not

00:29:13.540 --> 00:29:15.310 align:middle line:90%
a criminal matter.

00:29:15.310 --> 00:29:17.900 align:middle line:84%
So you're going to be
exposed to it every day.

00:29:17.900 --> 00:29:20.640 align:middle line:84%
There are a number
of ads, print ads.

00:29:20.640 --> 00:29:24.930 align:middle line:84%
In the book, I show
you several print ads

00:29:24.930 --> 00:29:28.620 align:middle line:84%
that have been specifically
designed to embed sex

00:29:28.620 --> 00:29:32.500 align:middle line:90%
and demonic taboos, et cetera.

00:29:32.500 --> 00:29:34.370 align:middle line:84%
And a lot of people
say, well, why would

00:29:34.370 --> 00:29:36.180 align:middle line:90%
you embed a demonic taboo?

00:29:36.180 --> 00:29:39.230 align:middle line:84%
I get the sex, because
that gets my attention,

00:29:39.230 --> 00:29:44.130 align:middle line:84%
and then my attention
remembers, oh, Imperial Whiskey.

00:29:44.130 --> 00:29:46.420 align:middle line:90%
But why the taboos?

00:29:46.420 --> 00:29:49.280 align:middle line:84%
And they're just as
powerful as the sex.

00:29:49.280 --> 00:29:52.535 align:middle line:84%
We all have what Freud
called a Thanatos urge.

00:29:52.535 --> 00:29:55.080 align:middle line:90%


00:29:55.080 --> 00:30:00.010 align:middle line:84%
Bungee jumping, skydiving--
all these things

00:30:00.010 --> 00:30:04.800 align:middle line:84%
that we do to terrify ourselves,
to get this big thrill,

00:30:04.800 --> 00:30:08.610 align:middle line:84%
they're all about reminding
ourselves that we're alive.

00:30:08.610 --> 00:30:11.240 align:middle line:84%
We have this death
urge that kind of

00:30:11.240 --> 00:30:14.760 align:middle line:84%
sits there, because after
all, we know it's coming.

00:30:14.760 --> 00:30:16.830 align:middle line:90%
It's just a matter of when.

00:30:16.830 --> 00:30:23.530 align:middle line:84%
And so these kinds of
demonic images, they

00:30:23.530 --> 00:30:25.860 align:middle line:84%
have just as much
power as the sex.

00:30:25.860 --> 00:30:29.370 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How do they plant--
when you say subliminal,

00:30:29.370 --> 00:30:32.790 align:middle line:84%
give me a definition of
what that actually is.

00:30:32.790 --> 00:30:37.790 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Well, now you're
going to cross several areas.

00:30:37.790 --> 00:30:41.080 align:middle line:84%
We can say, technically
today, that if you

00:30:41.080 --> 00:30:43.317 align:middle line:84%
had a Macintosh
computer on your desk,

00:30:43.317 --> 00:30:44.400 align:middle line:90%
and you see a lot of that.

00:30:44.400 --> 00:30:45.960 align:middle line:90%
That's why I say Mac.

00:30:45.960 --> 00:30:50.610 align:middle line:84%
And it was up, and you could
see the Mac logo, well,

00:30:50.610 --> 00:30:52.630 align:middle line:90%
that's a product placement.

00:30:52.630 --> 00:30:56.080 align:middle line:84%
And that product placement
doesn't consciously

00:30:56.080 --> 00:30:58.210 align:middle line:90%
get recognized.

00:30:58.210 --> 00:31:01.210 align:middle line:84%
But it definitely
influences you.

00:31:01.210 --> 00:31:04.470 align:middle line:84%
It absolutely has been
proven to influence you.

00:31:04.470 --> 00:31:09.540 align:middle line:84%
So whether it's an automobile,
a computer, or what have you,

00:31:09.540 --> 00:31:11.960 align:middle line:84%
that has a very
powerful influence.

00:31:11.960 --> 00:31:14.930 align:middle line:84%
And because it's not
consciously recognized,

00:31:14.930 --> 00:31:18.000 align:middle line:84%
some people will call it
a subliminal influence.

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:22.290 align:middle line:84%
I think of that as really
being a supraliminal influence

00:31:22.290 --> 00:31:24.570 align:middle line:90%
because we could see it.

00:31:24.570 --> 00:31:26.399 align:middle line:90%
A true subliminal influence--

00:31:26.399 --> 00:31:27.190 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Is hidden.

00:31:27.190 --> 00:31:28.530 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: That's right.

00:31:28.530 --> 00:31:34.080 align:middle line:84%
And your perceptual mechanism
is not made in such a way

00:31:34.080 --> 00:31:37.770 align:middle line:84%
that you're going to
distinguish it, recognize it.

00:31:37.770 --> 00:31:39.700 align:middle line:90%
You're going to process it.

00:31:39.700 --> 00:31:41.870 align:middle line:90%
A neuron's gonna fire.

00:31:41.870 --> 00:31:44.360 align:middle line:84%
But you're not
going to recognize

00:31:44.360 --> 00:31:46.420 align:middle line:90%
what you're processing.

00:31:46.420 --> 00:31:51.450 align:middle line:84%
In visual, usually, I've
given you-- in the book,

00:31:51.450 --> 00:31:54.340 align:middle line:84%
I show you an
actual layout where

00:31:54.340 --> 00:32:00.700 align:middle line:84%
we take a rendition-- this
is an airbrush drawing--

00:32:00.700 --> 00:32:02.720 align:middle line:84%
and it has all of
the symbols in it,

00:32:02.720 --> 00:32:06.630 align:middle line:84%
including the phallic
symbols, et cetera.

00:32:06.630 --> 00:32:10.840 align:middle line:84%
And then we get a model, and
we get the model to pose.

00:32:10.840 --> 00:32:13.950 align:middle line:84%
And so perhaps she
has a glass that

00:32:13.950 --> 00:32:17.740 align:middle line:84%
appears to be a glass of
whiskey with ice cubes in it,

00:32:17.740 --> 00:32:19.760 align:middle line:90%
about to put it in her mouth.

00:32:19.760 --> 00:32:22.210 align:middle line:10%
And the way it's
airbrushed, you look at it,

00:32:22.210 --> 00:32:25.070 align:middle line:10%
and you don't see anything
out of the ordinary other

00:32:25.070 --> 00:32:28.080 align:middle line:10%
than a very beautiful
woman with some

00:32:28.080 --> 00:32:33.040 align:middle line:10%
suggestive-- a collar and
whatnot around her, very

00:32:33.040 --> 00:32:34.770 align:middle line:10%
suggestive, beautiful woman.

00:32:34.770 --> 00:32:38.120 align:middle line:84%
But when you start
pulling this ad apart--

00:32:38.120 --> 00:32:40.290 align:middle line:84%
and one of the things
that I do in the book

00:32:40.290 --> 00:32:44.060 align:middle line:84%
is show you an actual
advertising manual and an ad.

00:32:44.060 --> 00:32:47.860 align:middle line:84%
And they explain
in their words--

00:32:47.860 --> 00:32:53.390 align:middle line:84%
